'''Nellie Hermann''' is an American writer who lives in New York, and the author of two novels. Her debut novel was ''The Cure for Grief'' (Simon & Schuster, 2008);<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/21/books/21newly-sub.html|title=Newly Released|last=Bloom|first=Julie|date=21 August 2008|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref> her second novel, ''The Season of Migration'', deals with [[Vincent van Gogh]]'s time in Belgium, and uses the artist's correspondence along with fabricated letters.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bostonglobe.com/arts/books/2015/01/08/book-review-the-season-migration-nellie-hermann/EuBaZGJmyc0B78hN5VBd6M/story.html|title=Book review: ''The Season of Migration'' by Nellie Hermann|last=Stuart|first=Jan|date=8 January 2015|work=[[The Boston Globe]]|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/25/books/review/the-season-of-migration-by-nellie-hermann.html?emc=edit_bk_20150123&nl=books&nlid=22512753&_r=0|title=''The Season of Migration'', by Nellie Hermann|last=Cohen|first=Leah Hager|date=23 January 2015|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref>

She was born in Boston, and attended [[Brown University]] before getting her MFA at [[Columbia University]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://authors.simonandschuster.com/Nellie-Hermann/46108771|title=Nellie Hermann|publisher=[[Simon & Schuster]]|accessdate=23 January 2015}}</ref>

